racteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Byron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Byram (Yorkshire), named with Old English <i>bȳrum</i> ‘at the cattle sheds’, dative plural of <i>bȳre</i> ‘byre’. This name has occasionally been adopted as a Jewish surname, presumably as an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish name."],"variants":[{"name":"Byrom","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]},{"name":"Byrum","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]},{"name":"Byram","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Byron of Melling Manor was born in 1237, in Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Robert de Byron, was 28 and his mother, Maud de Clayton, was 7. He married wife Robert de Byron before 1272, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1280, at the age of 43."},"et":{"Cir 1237–1280":"1237–1280","1237–1280":"1237–1280","1254–Male":"1254–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1293–1361":"1293–1361","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1230–1248":"1230–1248","after 1248":"pärast 1248","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","Cir 1237":"1237","1210":"1210","1254":"1254","1230":"1230","1361":"1361","before 1272":"enne 1272","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Melling, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","Melling, Lancashire, England":"Melling, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"Cir 1237–1280":"1237–1280","1237–1280":"1237–1280","1254–Male":"1254–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1293–1361":"1293–1361","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1230–1248":"1230–1248","after 1248":"1248 jälkeen","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","Cir 1237":"1237","1210":"1210","1254":"1254","1230":"1230","1361":"1361","before 1272":"ennen vuotta 1272","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Melling, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Melling, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","Melling, Lancashire, England":"Melling, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"Cir 1237–1280":"1237–1280","1237–1280":"1237–1280","1254–Male":"1254–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1293–1361":"1293–1361","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1230–1248":"1230–1248","after 1248":"après 1248","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","